segments.text: Let's back up, though.
You start the first grade, and where was the school?
What school did you attend, and where was it?
It was in the big old building.
I don't need a map.
But it was on campus.
Yeah, right there by the
By the pavilion?
Well, down from the pavilion.
Let's see.
Well, see, this was a quality road right here.
Like that.
You got up here and you went that way and you went in behind the academic building.
Okay.
And this built a road right here.
Mm-hmm.
It's the last building on this side.
One, there's another one right there beside it.
One of them was for the, I think, for the extension service, and one was for the... Now, I remember where Old Science Hall was.
Was it near that?
Old Science Hall.
Mm-hmm.
The red brick building tore down about 40 years ago?
No, there were two.
I think they're still standing.
Okay.
About how many first graders were there year-to-year?
They was, oh, I guess they were about 25.
Now, and were they from all across this south part of the county, or were they only from the campus?
No, they brought in the ones from the south.
There were farms all through this area, see?
And those kids walked to school.
What was the name of the, was it the A&M Consolidated School then?
What was the name of it?
Well, you see, that's where, that's what happened.
It was not a consolidated thing.
The state had laws for school districts like that, but the A&M campus was not a school district.
Okay.
And the A&M, the budget of the A&M campus gave so much money to this combination of school districts.
It was just a, it was just an association.
It wasn't, it was legalized by what the legislature gave the college to give to the school districts.
Were all 11 grades in the same building?
Not then.
So you had an elementary building and a high school?
No, we had no schools.
No, I mean on the campus.
Well, we had no schools.
They were on the campus, but they were in various buildings.
Oh, okay.
Now, where did the teachers come from?
They hired them.
But they live on campus?
Uh, yeah, they did, they did.
They, uh, I don't know about those, the younger, I know that, um, Ethel Waldron, who was the oldest girl, she told me one time that, uh,
she was in that same building that I was in, right on the corner.
Later on, they built a white building down here, straight down south of that.
I think they later called it the Music Hall or something like that.
Now they built that building, this wooden building.
And they built that, and when they did,
they started having us at the regular school.
So you got up and walked a short distance from where you lived to the school.
Dad took me.
Dad carried us in a car.
Really?
Yeah.
I had two sisters, too.
As you think about it now and look back,
What was the quality of the elementary grades you took here on campus, the first few grades?
Was it a good school?
Yes, I guess it was for what they did.
I mean, it was all right.
My problem was the fact that I had astigmatism and I couldn't read.
I'm also a dialectic.
I don't know right from left.
And so I was always, they were always waking me up or doing something, I don't know, yelling at me.
It didn't make any difference.
But we got an education.
We got a good education.
In the elementary years, who were some of your closest buddies?
Lucian Morgan, Charles Ritchie.
Ritchie?
Ritchie.
Ritchie.
He was head of the Civil Engineering Department.
And Dean Bolton, he had a boy.
And the FAPS boy, he died.
That's the only one I ever saw that was dead at that time.
But they had, and the Billsies had two boys, and one of them died.
What kind of mischief did you little boys create?
What'd y'all do for pranks?
Oh, there's a, the chemistry department had a building, a tin building, right back here, behind me, between the, the old chemistry building
And the Aggie Engineering Building.
The Aggie Engineering Building had a lawn on the front of it.
And it had a filling station over on the right here.
But we would come up there and they had some men working in there and we'd take a rock and throw up there and hit it with a tin roof, you know, and they were working there.
I guess they got used to it.
Oh, you were just always around someplace.
Another thing too, there were some old World War I trenches.
You never heard this story before.
There were some old World War I trenches that we played in.
Where were they?
Going towards College Park, you know, there's a dip there.
Well, they're building that gully.
And they were just like the pictures in it that we're showing on TV today.
Did they use them for training?
I guess they would have.
So you all played in those trenches?
Yeah.
Yeah, we played in those.
Did y'all ever make any noise in the academic buildings, you little boys?
Our biggest, or what we did, was taking, at the end of the semester, they had a requirement that you had to clean your room and leave it in good order.
The students?
Yes, students.
through the hall.
We went down those halls.
I walked home with enough alarm clocks.
And I'd take them apart.
The other thing was that they had those old coal hot stoves.
Brown coal oil stoves?
Well, there were usually about four.
Oh, okay.
There were four burners.
They had this big old jar sitting up on the end.
And so then they would, I'd go get those.
I don't know how I got them home, but I'd get two or three of those and I'd take them
We'd throw them in the garbage after I got through Pink Park.
Just take all the screws out of them.
And then my father got me an eighth-inch pipe.
He got me 12-inch lengths of eighth-inch pipe.
elbows, some tees, some caps, some couplings, and he got that from, and I remember when he brought it home, and he said, mother, you got some of my lye?
And she said, yeah.
And so they took a big old pan, set it up on that big range,
and filled it with water and he dumped all those in there.
He cleaned all the grease off of them.
I haven't got pieces of those in my farm yet.
You could scroll together like this.
And then there was another one later on was a little what's called a rector's set.
You remember all those?
We had those.
We didn't have a lot of toys, but we didn't have any radio, TV, or anything.
The first time I ever heard of radio was in 1926.
Do you remember, did your father buy radio then, or what was the occasion?
Occasionally we went down to the Bentley's apartment on South Bryan Street, about where Connolly's is today.
There was a house in there and they were renting that house.
He was, Bentley was one of our professors there.
And that's the first time I ever heard a radio.
We sat there and listened to it.
Now you had a different society, your society was entirely different too.
Sure.

You had, you had heads of the departments, you had professors that were working, which in there, well I guess you, like the Air Force, or like the Army, you never, we never did go see some of the help.
They had people, white people, who did a lot of work for us.
And they had a lot of Negro people, too.
While you were a little kid, elementary school, where did your mother in those years, where did she buy her groceries?
From Luke and Charlie's.
Luke and Charlie's?
Yeah, Luke and Charlie's.
Where was that?
Northgate.
Okay, how big was it?
It serviced the whole college.
Is that right?
And did they deliver for her?
Yeah.
Now you're saying L-U-K-E, Luke, Luke and Charlie.
It's Luke, I think it's Luke Patronella.
Okay.
And I don't remember what the, or Charlie was his last name.
And then occasionally, and then to buy other things.
The bill, the mother ran there about $75 a month.
And then would you go down, would the family go downtown, Brian, for shopping, other shopping?
A little.
But Dad loved to take us downtown.
He's
We'd go down there across from the, where the LaSalle, the Marisco building, on that street there, on the corner, right there on the corner across the street.
The Watkins men sat right there on the corner.
He had a, he had a, that with all those pharmaceuticals.
And he was there.
Then the Negroes, they had a wagon yard where the food town is today, down on North Main Street.
That was a wagon yard.
And they came in here on Saturday night.
On Saturday, they came in on Saturday.
From out in the country?
Out in the country, all over.
They'd drive a wagon in there.
And I guess they drove it home afterwards or something or something.
Or maybe they stayed there.
I don't know.
But they'd always coming out through there.
And then there was white people in there and everybody else in there.
And Dad loved to just sit there and watch those people.
What was the big... Was there any big department store downtown?
Dry goods store?
Oh, yeah.
Edges.
Edges.
Okay.
And...
I don't know.
What's the name?
I don't know.
A.M. Waldrop?
A.M. Waldrop, yeah, they were there.
Waldrop's were there, and Edges, well, they always got a lot of stuff from there.
And Lester's later on came in.
How often did the family, or your mom and dad at least, how often did they go to Houston or Dallas?
Well, uh,
In the first few years, we went to Houston.
We would... Would you go by train or car?
No, we went by car.
It was a rough trip.
It took about four hours.
Three or four hours.
We used to buy stuff at... Foley's?
No, Foley one day.
Oh.
It was there.
They used to buy me clothes there.
It was a store right downtown on Main Street.
And we went there and they bought me pants that looked like jodhpurs.
And that's all I wore for a long time.
And then my father was head of the Ag Engineering Department.
He had to take care of the entire Ag Engineering Department.
So then the Hardware Implement Association
in Texas, came to the college and says, can you get us a man to run this organization?
So they asked Dad to do it.
And yeah, that was when that was.
And so he took the job on them.
They paid him an honorarium.
I think it was something in the early days of about $100 a month.
In addition to his... Salary.
To his campus responsibilities.
And they gave him a... Did that cause him to travel much?
Oh, a lot of times.
A lot of times.
He traveled.
And the reason I remember that, that far back,
One day we were going, and I went with him.
He was having a series of meetings in Waco.
And so we drove up there.
I know we were driving there in that 21 Dodge.
It took us four hours to get up there.
All gravel roads.
like that.
And so he, he says, son you gotta have a pair of long pants.
So we went to Cox's in Waco.
He bought me a pair of long pants.
That was the first time I'd ever had a pair of long pants.
That would be in
I would say it was about 1924 or something like that.
That's about when that was.
But his job as Secretary and Treasurer of the Hardware Association, I traveled with him a lot.
What were the primary implement companies that were supplying farm implements in those days?
Oh, IEC.
International Harvester.
John Deere.
Ford.
Ford had some things, not that far back.
The first Ford was about 1937.
Yeah, but was Farmall back in the early 20s?
No.
I thought they were later, too.
When I was teaching, I taught at Tarleton in 35, 37, and the only one I had was IHC, it was a hormone.
Ford came on a year later, but the Ford had a lift on the back, which makes it, even today, my son has one of them.
We still keep it in Kipropa.
Were there, were there farm tractors in the 20s?
Oh, yeah.
Oh, yeah.
Uh, the college got two oil pools, and then we got one of them stuck out here, uh, right across from about where their farm, uh, you know,
Where you get flowers and stuff there.
A horticulture center?
No, right there on Old College Road.
Oh, oh, oh.
A student was driving and he lost it and he ran off in a big ditch.
We had a hell of a time pulling that thing out of there.
And then they got an aviary, which is big.
I like the aviary better.
It's an easy start.
Were Texas farmers using, that didn't have tractors, did they use horses or mules?
Which did they use most?
For plowing and... Down here, probably with mules.
Mules, mm-hmm.
What they had, horses.
Up north, you never, you very seldom saw mules.
Now, another thing about mules is that
you put a pair of mules together and one of them dies, you got it.
The other one won't make up.
I don't know why that is, but that's the truth.
And we had one, the college had a stallion, a horse stallion out of a mule.
which college has, I understand it somewhere.
But I used to, I used him in 37.
When I came back in 37, I brought a horse with me then.
I built a trailer and brought a horse with me.
And we used to take him over there.
This is right over here was the horse barn.
You know that?
The pavilion.
No.
The little one right beside it.
Oh, yes, yes.
That's a horse bar.
The old pavilion is still there.
And then the... Where the golf course is now was the cow pasture.
And then north of that... All of it was cow pasture.
Oh, all of that was cow pasture.
And then the roads out there, there wasn't any roads out there.
They were just open pasture where the veterinary people kept their stock
In the early 20s, the first years your family was here, where did you all go to church?
Gone home.
And did just about the whole campus attend?
Yeah.
Now, who did the sermon?
Reverend Matthews.
What denomination was he?
I don't know.
Was there Sunday school?
Sunday school.
We went to Sunday school.
And I was in the class with Dr. Reed, who was head of the poultry department.
Were there any churches at what we now call Northgate in the 20s?
They started up then.
They started up then.
What were the first ones that you remember?
The Methodists and the Baptists.
The Baptists were later.
But the first church, the tabernacle back there, was built by the Methodists.
It is a big old tabernacle.
It's a very big old thing.
I mean, it wasn't, it had windows in it, of course, but it was just a really, and I had to help get the sewer line in there.
And my father did a lot of that work for these people around here, but he had several
students that were quite competent.
One was .
I worked for him.
We dug a trench across the, from that old tabernacle, which is right there, where the church is now, across that street right there.
And it went back into the college system down here somewhere.
I don't know just where it went.
You know, that didn't bother me.
When I had to crawl in those things and check the grade on them, they thought, oh hell, I was a pretty good engineer before I was 12 years old.
Now, when you arrived, the campus had its own power system already, and the sewer system
or was on the campus.
It had a sewer system which was mainly aligned to the to the Brandeis River.
They pumped it out there and pumped it to the river.
There's a pipeline down there someplace.
Back to religion, were there many Catholic or Jewish
people here then?
They would have their meeting places on Sunday.
The college opened up the buildings for them.
Then you had a compulsory sermon for the students.
What if they didn't attend?
What happened?
They were disciplined.
See, you had a, you had a, just like you do today, the same thing with the Corps.
You had a Corps commander for each company, and he was responsible to... For getting them there?
I don't know.
Well, he was responsible, yeah, for the training and also the
And then you had, we had 16 army officers here on campus, lived with us.
Were there anyone, was there anyone on campus who had been a kind of a World War I hero?
No.
No, those people we had were real army, a real army or air.
We didn't have any air force.
We did have cavalry.
And you see, here's what happened.
They would assign an officer and his family to the college for four years.
if he formed outright.
And they could actually ask for the fifth year if they wanted to.
And so I only saw one man that I know of that they pulled him off after one year because he was playing around.
When Dr. Bezell went to the University of Oklahoma, who followed him?
Did
Is that when Walton became president?
Yeah, I guess so.
What kind of a president was he?
Who, Walton?
Mm-hmm.
He was a good man.
Good man.
See, he was a man that could get up and talk to people.
Mm-hmm.
That is the most important part of a professor's life.
His ability to talk and relate to people.
Walton was great at it.
His family was...
I couldn't say much more.
And... Oh, Ethel Walton, the oldest girl, married Burgess.
And they formed what's called South Oakwood.
and later they went and formed North Oakwood, which I have a home.
Mm-hmm, mm-hmm.
Oh, now, this is Herschel Burgess?
Yeah.
Mm-hmm.
And where South Oakwood is now, when you got here, what was it, just open land?
No, it belonged to the, it belonged to the Shoots.
But was it just...
It was a farm.
A farm?
They had a family down there that raised crops in the lower end of it.
About when were those streets laid out?
Well, the South Side Development Company, which is College Park, the
Charter was granted in 1920 or 21.
My father was a part of it.
There was Dan Schultz, there was Lancaster, I don't remember what his first name was, Dr. Clark, and then there was Burgess, I mean
There was Dorney, and then there was a man who was like Dr. Fraps.
He was in Dr. Fraps's outfit.
He buried over there.
They formed a company and they bought that land.
